>>gets to the wheels. in this respect they are at a disadvantage to a manual. >only when the torque converter is not locked up. there are autos out there
>with converter lock up in 2nd, 3rd and 4th gears. w/r/t performance, converter lockup is purely irrelevant. the lockup only
occurs at light throttle settings and serves only to improve mpg. mind you,
a converter clutch does a lovely job of improving mpg, but the additional
mechanical advantage of the converter gives you more acceleration (vs. locked
converter clutch) than its inherent losses take away. michael t. chaffee <----email <----nextmail
